This Norton Critical Edition presents twelve of  Tolstoy best-known stories, based on the  Louise and Aylmer Maude translations (except  lyosha Gorshok?, which have been revised by  the editor for enhanced comprehension and  annotated for student readers. The Second  Edition newly includes  Prisoner in the  Caucasus,?ather Sergius,?and fter the  Ball,?in addition to Michael Katz new  translation of lyosha Gorshok.?Together these stories represent the best of the author short  fiction before War and Peace and after  Anna Karenina.ackgrounds and Sources?includes two  Tolstoy memoirs, A History of Yesterday (1851) and The Memoirs of a Madman  (1884), as well as entriesxpanded in the  Second Editionrom Tolstoy iary for 1855? and selected letters (1858?5) that shed light  on the author creative process.riticism?collects twenty-three essays by  Russian and western scholars, six of which are  new to this Second Edition. Interpretations  focus both on Tolstoy language and art and on  specific themes and motifs in individual  stories. Contributors include John M. Kopper,  Gary Saul Morson, N. G. Chernyshevsky, Mikhail  Bakhtin, Harsha Ram, John Bayley, Vladimir  Nabokov, Ruth Rischin, Margaret Ziolkowski, and  Donald Barthelme.A Chronology of  Tolstoy life and work and an updated Selected  Bibliography are also included.
